<subSubSection box="[199,1205,1519,1545]" pageId="15" pageNumber="396" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1086,1653]" box="[199,1205,1519,1545]" pageId="15" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1519,1545]" pageId="15" pageNumber="396">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after the pair of spines on the apex of connective stem.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="396" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1086,1653]" pageId="15" pageNumber="396">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1555,1581]" pageId="15" pageNumber="396">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1934" box="[885,1030,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecaloidella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[885,1030,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="396">Hecaloidella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the unique shape of the connective and aedeagus (see description) and in the female by the greatly prolonged pregenital sternite posteromedially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
